pr_review_body:
Thanks. I seems we have the chance to reuse the code for both cases:
```
    @API
    def mdns_query(self, dst='ff02::fb', service='_meshcop._udp.local', addrs_blacklist=[]):
        output = self.bash('python3 ~/repo/openthread/tests/scripts/thread-cert/find_border_agents.py')
        
        # For BBR-TC-03 or DH test cases (empty arguments) just send a query
        if dst == 'ff02::fb' and not addrs_blacklist:
            return

        # For MATN-TC-17 and MATN-TC-18 use Zeroconf to get the BBR address and border agent port
        for line in output:
            print(line)
            alias, link_local_addr, port, thread_status = eval(line)
            if thread_status == 2 and link_local_addr:
                if (dst and link_local_addr in dst) or (link_local_addr not in addrs_blacklist):
                    return '%s%%%s' % (link_local_addr, self.backboneNetif), port

        raise Exception('No active Border Agents found')
```

> Do we need a test for this one? I couldn’t find where to add it.

I...I...how are there no tests for this modifier? :confused: 

@adybbroe @mraspaud do you remember if there are tests for this somewhere? And @yukaribbba yes there needs to be tests added. I made some other comments inline.

@Gaurav7888 welcome to PyTorch community! LGTM.

To merge this you will need to complete the CLA signing (you only need to do it once). Once the tests pass we can merge to master.

Edit: Unfortunately the failing tests are related to the change. More investigation is needed.

@benjyw was extremely patient in describing to me the relevance of this PR in the short term, and noted especially that the act of merging the `python_awslambda()` and `python_binary()` targets (proposed in #10893) would be a much bigger change than I had previously realized. I will be thinking about that separately and asynchronously.

After thinking a lot about it and getting more familiar with the implementation along with extremely helpful context from @Eric-Arellano, I will push any further longer-term abstract ideas about how to improve the BUILD file API for plugin authors into docs and out of the way of active work. The change in this diff (merging awslambda and binary into a single build goal) is 100% reasonable and I deeply appreciate the patience demonstrated in explaining it to me so many times.

Thanks to @stuhood as well for stepping in and recognizing the miscommunication here. That was extremely helpful.

The body of both functions is very much the same, the only difference is one calls to `git_merge_base_many` and the other one calls to `git_merge_base_octopus`.

Instead please write a static function, so there's not duplicated code. Then it may look something like:

```c
typedef int (*git_merge_base_xxx_t)(git_oid *out, git_repository *repo, size_t length, const git_oid input_array[]);

static PyObject *
merge_base_xxx(Repository *self, PyObject *args, git_merge_base_xxx_t git_merge_base_xxx)
{
   [...]
}

PyObject *
Repository_merge_base_octopus(Repository *self, PyObject *args)
{
    return merge_base_xxx(self, args, &git_merge_base_octopus);
}
```

The changes look right, and I'm approving this PR. After a brief discussion over on slack, it doesn't look like there are any complaints about the change to the default behavior. 

Since @annawoodard and @ravihansa3000 have more experience with checkpointing in practice, I'm hoping they'd chime in soon, if they have any reservations against this change.

@benclifford it looks like there's a merge conflict that needs fixing.

@mcdo0486, this looks good to me, even though I am not entirely sure I can understand all the ramifications of the changes.
I wonder, if there could be any issue of backward compatibility. Do you have any comment on this ?
Before merging, I would prefer to have a second opinion from other maintainers.
